Summary: Explains the concept of performance bottlenecks and introduces profiling as a method for identifying them in CPU-bound applications.

Measuring performance
We have to know where the "bottlenecks" are to know how to speed up our program. Bottlenecks are the slowest parts of the program that limit the rate that everything can progress. Focusing on bottlenecks allows us to concentrate our efforts on optimizing the areas which will give us the greatest speed improvement, instead of spending a lot of time optimizing functions that will lead to small performance improvements.

For the CPU, the easiest way to identify bottlenecks is to use a profiler.
---CHUNK---
Document: CPU Optimization
Path: godot/tutorials/performance/cpu_optimization.rst
Summary: This section explains how to use Godot's built-in CPU profiler to identify performance bottlenecks in your project.
CPU profilers run alongside your program and take timing measurements to determine the proportion of time spent in each function. The Godot IDE has a built-in profiler that must be manually started and stopped, as recording timing measurements can significantly slow down your project. After profiling, you can review the results for a frame.

Note: We can see the cost of built-in processes such as physics and audio, as well as the cost of our own scripting functions. Note: Time spent waiting for various built-in servers may not be counted in the profilers; this is a known bug.

When a project is running slowly, you will often see an obvious function or process taking a lot more time than others. This is your primary bottleneck, and you can usually increase speed by optimizing this area. For more information about using Godot's built-in profiler, see the debugger panel documentation.
---CHUNK---
